{{Nihongo|'''Umi Hachimangū'''|宇美八幡宮|}} is a [[Shinto]] [[Shinto shrine|shrine]] located in [[Umi, Fukuoka|Umi]], [[:en:Fukuoka Prefecture|Fukuoka Prefecture]], [[:en:Japan|Japan]]. It is dedicated to [[:en:Emperor Ōjin|Emperor Ōjin]], [[:en:Empress Jingū|Empress Jingū]], [[Tamayori-hime (mother of Jimmu)|Tamayori-bime]], [[Sumiyoshi sanjin]] and [[Izanagi]]. In the former [[Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines]], it was classified as a prefectural shrine (県社, ''kensha'').

==History==
The shrine is venerated as the legendary place where [[:en:Empress Jingū|Empress Jingū]] safely gave birth to the future [[:en:Emperor Ōjin|Emperor Ōjin]], and is still patronized by those praying for safe childbirth and smooth child rearing.

==Natural Treasures==
The cluster of giant [[:en:Cinnamomum camphora|camphor trees]] called ''Kada’s Forest'' <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.crossroadfukuoka.jp/en/event/?mode=detail&isSpot=1&id=4000000000373 |title=Umi Shrine |publisher=[[:en:Fukuoka Prefecture|Fukuoka Prefecture]] |accessdate=19 September 2011}}</ref> (including the two old camphors that have been deemed [[Monuments of Japan|Natural Treasures]], "Yufuta’s Forest" and "Kinukake’s Forest").

